====Usage notes====
A common misconception is that {{m-self|en|wherefore}} means ''where''; it is occasionally so used in [[retellings]] of Romeo and Juliet — often for comedic effect. In ''Romeo and Juliet'', the meaning of “Wherefore art thou Romeo?” ([[s:The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet#SCENE II. Capulet.27s orchard.|Act 2, scene 2, line 33]]) is not “''Where'' are you, Romeo?” but “''Why'' are you Romeo?” (i.e. “Why did you have to be a Montague?”).<ref>{{R:Phrase Finder|entry=O Romeo, Romeo! wherefore art thou Romeo?|url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/O%20Romeo%2C%20Romeo%21%20wherefore%20art%20thou%20Romeo%3F.html|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref>

